Predicting survival in the Titanic shipwreck!¶

Tech talk S04 E07 at iTech

By: Caroline Costa caroline.costa@itech.media

Aims¶

  • We want to build a machine learning model that can predict Jack's death and Rose's survival
  • We want to understand why they survived or not

Approach¶

We will build a tree-based classification model that can predict Jack's and Rose's fate in the shipwreck and use SHAP to understand the contribution of individual features on the predictions.

We will follow the steps below:

  • Exploration: Investigate trends and patterns in the data
  • Pre-processing: Prepare data for modelling
  • Modelling: Build classifiers and experiment with different parameters
  • Refinement: Refine the model by tuning hyperparameters and improving the data
  • Understanding the model's decisions: Investigate feature contributions in global and individual predictions

Feature descriptions¶

PassengerID: ID number

Survived: Survival 0 = No, 1 = Yes

Pclass: Ticket class 1 = 1st, 2 = 2nd, 3 = 3rd

Name: Name

Sex: Sex - Male or Female

Age: age in years

SibSp: # of siblings / spouses aboard the Titanic

ParCh: # of parents / children aboard the Titanic

Ticket: Ticket number

Fare: Passenger fare

Cabin: Cabin number

Embarked: Port of Embarkation C = Cherbourg, Q = Queenstown, S = Southampton

Devide into training and test sets¶

Before we dive into our data, we want to first set a test aside. We'll use the test set to evaluate our model on data neither nor the model has seen during training. This will avoid what is called snooping bias, where we influence the outcome of the model with too much knowledge of the data.

Let's also check how much data we have in each class. As the plot below shows, more passengers died than survived, but the imbalance is not too bad! Let's just make sure both training and test sets

Pre-processing¶

Prepare the data for modelling

Create transformation pipeline¶

Based on the analysis above, we need to:

  • Impute missing data
  • Transform features from categorical to numerical, as the ML models we will use do not accept categorical features
  • Normalize the data, which currently has very different scales. This might not be required for tree-based models, but most ML models require this step
In [15]:
# create data transformation pipelines for categorical and numerical features separately
num_cols = ['Age', 'SibSp', 'Parch', 'Fare']
cat_cols = ['Pclass', 'Sex', 'Embarked']

# numerical features
num_pipeline = Pipeline([
    ('imputer', SimpleImputer(strategy='median')), # impute missing values
    ('std_scaler', StandardScaler()) # normalize data: standardization better when there outliers
])

# categorical features
cat_pipeline = Pipeline([
    ('imputer', SimpleImputer(strategy='most_frequent')), # impute missing values
    ('one_hot', OneHotEncoder(drop='if_binary')) # categorical -> numerical
])

# build full pipeline and fit to training data
full_pipeline = ColumnTransformer([
    ('num', num_pipeline, num_cols),
    ('cat', cat_pipeline, cat_cols)
]).fit(titanic_train)

Modelling¶

Define an evaluation metric¶

For consistency with Kaggle, we will use accuracy, which gives a percentage of correct predictions, to measure model performance.

Accuracy is not always advisable as a classification metric, as it can be misleading, especially in unbalanced datasets. Typically, we would look at precision and recall. Have a look here: https://medium.com/@shrutisaxena0617/precision-vs-recall-386cf9f89488

Kaggle's leaderboard top accuracy stands at 0.8133. How close do we need to get? There's always an easy trap with Data Science models: never ending projects chasing after high model accuracy!

Let's be realistic and set our "good enough" target to be up to 5% less, so 77.26 accuracy.

We also need to think about metrics that measure impact/value. That doesn't apply here, but think about:

  • What accuracy/precision/recall mean in terms such as time/money/lives saved?
  • What is the cost of getting our predictions wrong?

Esblishing a baseline¶

Let's start with a simple model that uses a single decision tree. A decision tree classifier learns simple decision rules inferred from the data features.

Advantages:

  • Simple and easy to setup
  • Explainable (if limited to a few levels)

Disadvantages:

  • Prone to overfitting: can easily learn the training set "by heart" but will not generalize to unseen data
  • Requires little data preparation: no need for scaling or one-hot encoding
  • Can be unstable because small variations in the data might result in a completely different tree
  • Decision tree learners create biased trees if some classes dominate

More info: https://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/tree.html#tree

In [20]:

Try a more complex model¶

Bring out the big guns, aka, XGBoost!

XGBoost is based on the ML framework of Gradient Boosting. The general idea of Gradient Boosting is to incrementally add decision trees to an ensemble to correct its predecessor, where the new predictor is fitted to the residual errors made by the previous predictor. So, at each iteration, the model tries to improve on its errors.

How does it work?

  • Iteratively learning an ensemble of weak models on subsets of the data: can be done in parallel!
  • Weighting each weak prediction according to each weak learners performance
  • Combine the weighted predictions to obtain a single weighted prediction that is much better than the individual predictions themselves

XGBoost provides a library with a scalable, portable and accurate implementation of boosting. It is often a champion in Kaggle competitions and can even beat Neural Networks for certain problems.

When to use XGBoost

  • Large number of training samples: <1000 and >100 features
  • Mixture of categorical and numeric features or only numeric features
  • Categorical only: catboost

When not to use XGBoost

  • Image recognition, computer vision, natural language processing and understanding problems: these are best solved using deep-learning approaches
  • Small training set, with less training samples than features: these usually require Bayesian models

Check it out here: https://xgboost.readthedocs.io/en/stable/index.html

In [31]:
def train_eval_model(params, dtrain, dtest, train_labels, test_labels):
    # train
    xgb_clf = xgb.train(params, dtrain)

    # run prediction
    xgb_train_preds = xgb_clf.predict(dtrain)
    xgb_test_preds = xgb_clf.predict(dtest)
    
    # compute accuracy
    xgb_train_acr = accuracy_score(train_labels, xgb_train_preds)
    xgb_test_acr = accuracy_score(test_labels, xgb_test_preds)
    print('XGBoost accuracy on train {:1.4f} and test {:1.4f}'.format(xgb_train_acr, xgb_test_acr))
    
    return xgb_clf
In [32]:
xgb_clf = train_eval_model(params, dtrain, dtest, titanic_labels_train_prep, titanic_labels_test_prep)

XGBoost accuracy on train 0.7682 and test 0.7653

What else could we try?¶

  • Investigate if there are any subsets of the data where the model is performing poorly. Could we get more data? Could we improve that subset?
  • Feature engineering: try combining and creating new features based on current ones
  • Try different models such as Random Forest, LightGBM, Neural Networks, etc.
  • Research what others have done: https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/titanic/code
  • Re-trace your steps: we performed a lot of pre-processing steps without measuring the impact on the model! Consider using a tool for experiment tracking such as MLflow: https://mlflow.org/docs/latest/tracking.html

Other things to consider¶

  • Do we need higher accuracy? Consider the cost (time, compute resources) versus benefit (impact, value)
  • Stay focused on your aims: and don't get lost in the accuracy rabbit hole!

Understanding the model's decisions¶

We will SHAP for this task, as it is more robust and accurate than tree-based feature importances.

SHAP (SHapley Additive exPlanations) is a game theory approach to explain the output of any machine learning model. It connects optimal credit allocation with local explanations using the classic Shapley values from game theory and their related extensions.

Essentially, the Shapley value is the average expected marginal contribution of one player after all possible combinations have been considered. It helps to determine a payoff for all of the players when each player might have contributed more or less than the others.

An interesting article about it: https://towardsdatascience.com/interpretable-machine-learning-with-xgboost-9ec80d148d27

Link to library: https://github.com/slundberg/shap

Feature contributions¶

Predicting individual cases¶

We'll use our best model and make predictions on the test set, then see the result for Jack and Rose.

We'll also use the SHAP force plot to understand the prediction. In this plot, features pushing the prediction higher (survival) are shown in red, those pushing the prediction lower (death) are in blue
